{"ts": "2026-06-09T18:01:56.480701+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 450, "prompt_tokens": 10044, "total_tokens": 10494, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 181, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 9856}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "mimo-v2.5-pro", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "c1c9f448a0f042228630d5232fc04757", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ead8c-1557-71d0-a67f-5c5a75fe3aa0-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01_C03_A03", "issue_number": 1, "body": "Triage assessment:\n\nI've reviewed `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` and the migration files. The script indeed relies on shell glob expansion order (`for f in migrations/*.sql; do`) which is locale-dependent and can vary across filesystems and shells. The migration files have strict ordering requirements:\n\n1. `001_create_users.sql` creates the `users` table.\n2. `002_create_sessions.sql` creates the `sessions` table, referencing `users(id)`.\n3. `003_add_session_index.sql` creates an index on `sessions(user_id)`.\n\nIf the glob returns `003` before `002`, the index creation will fail because the `sessions` table doesn't yet exist. The reporter's description and the additional data point from Ubuntu confirm this is a reproducible bug on multiple platforms.\n\nThis is a valid bug that should be fixed. The suggested fix (explicit sorting) is correct and straightforward. I'm labeling this as a bug and priority/high."}, "id": "call_e995d464d3d04959ae24e5d8", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10044, "output_tokens": 450, "total_tokens": 10494, "input_toke